comments.body:
While I never had to override environment variables for a single command, I sometimes have to "push and pop" some other variables temporarily, usually when writing tests. So I would like the solution, probably a language construct, to also work for regular variables.

In C++ I wrote a little helper around `unique_ptr` with custom deleter to restore state at the end of the scope:

```cpp
auto x = 3;
{
    auto popGuard = tempChange(x, 5);  // need to give the finalizer object name to prevent immediate destruction
    ASSERT_EQ(x, 5);
}  // popGuard goes out of scope, its dtor restores original value
ASSERT_EQ(x, 3);
```

I think something similar could be written using C#'s `IDisposable` and `using tempChange(ref x, 5) { ... }` syntax. Does PowerShell support `using` blocks? If so, you just need to provide a helper.

@dkaszews Really API allows us to prepare environment block and use it to run subprocess. This doesn't change env block current process.
I made several PRs to solve this problem, but the code review process was so slow that I had to stop halfway through.
If anyone wants to continue this work, I'm willing to point the way and help.

@dkaszews 
>[..] and literally never run into this issue.

Good, I'm happy for you, but that tells me nothing because on the contrary, this issue has 30 comments and a whole lot of people showing interest in fixing it.

I'm lucky to not have to use PowerShell as my daily driver, or it would have 'daily driven' me insane. It's things like these that make it feel clumsy and it seems (based on what @iSazonov said) that attempts to improve it meet too much friction. Hence, the question "do you use your own shell".

So no, I'm not submitting a PR, because I simply don't care enough to fix someone else's product that I infrequently use. I'm simply bumping the tracker in hopes that the ergonomics of PS improve over time.

@iSazonov: Where did you get stuck? What's left? I couldn't find the branch in your (most recent) PS fork.
